Modify the given C++ code to include manual memory allocation for the arrays:

```c++
void multiplyArrays(int* array1, int* array2, int* result, int size) {
    int* array1Ptr = new int[size];
    int* array2Ptr = new int[size];
    int* resultPtr = new int[size];

    // Copy the values from the input arrays to the manually allocated arrays
    for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        *(array1Ptr + i) = *(array1 + i);
        *(array2Ptr + i) = *(array2 + i);
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        *(resultPtr + i) = *(array1Ptr + i) * *(array2Ptr + i);
    }

    // Copy the values from the resultPtr array to the result array
    for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        *(result + i) = *(resultPtr + i);
    }

    // Deallocate the manually allocated arrays
    delete[] array1Ptr;
    delete[] array2Ptr;
    delete[] resultPtr;
}
```

This modified code uses pointer arithmetic and manual memory allocation to perform the array multiplication without using array subscripts or built-in functions/operators to access or manipulate array elements. It ensures memory efficiency and avoids memory leaks by explicitly deallocating the manually allocated arrays at the end of the function. The time complexity of the solution is O(n), where n is the size of the arrays.

