```R
recursive_mean <- function(vec, n = length(vec), curr_sum = 0) {
  if (n == 0) {
    return(curr_sum / length(vec))
  } else {
    return(recursive_mean(vec, n - 1, curr_sum + vec[n]))
  }
}
```

In this function, `vec` is the input numerical vector, `n` is the length of the vector, and `curr_sum` keeps track of the current sum of the elements in the vector.

The base case is when `n` becomes 0, in which case we return the final mean by dividing the current sum by the length of the vector.

In the recursive step, we call the `recursive_mean` function again, but with `n` reduced by 1 and `curr_sum` updated by adding the current element of the vector.

By calling the function recursively `n` times, we achieve a time complexity of O(n), as desired.

